The start symbol S has only two binary productions:

1. S → NT13 NT5  
2. S → NT15 NT15  

Hence the string must be split into two contiguous parts that match one of these right-hand sides.

A.  S → NT13 NT5  
 • NT5 is a lexical (terminal-only) non-terminal.  
 • Therefore the second part of the split must be exactly one token produced by NT5.  
 • NT5 can generate { t11, t31, t34, t36, t38, t45, t60, t65, t77, t124, t130 }.  
 • The last token of the given string is t90, which is not in this set.  
 ⇒ No possible split realises the rule S → NT13 NT5.

B.  S → NT15 NT15  
 • If a substring begins with one of NT5’s tokens, NT15 could expand via NT15 → NT5 NT13; otherwise it must expand via NT15 → NT9 NT9 (or be a single-token lexical expansion).  
 • Inside our string the unique token t67 (position 20) can be produced only by NT15 (no other non-terminal can generate t67).  
 • Therefore t67 must be the single-token expansion of some NT15.  
 • But in S → NT15 NT15 each of the two NT15 constituents must itself generate a whole substring; hence one of those substrings would consist solely of t67.  
 • This forces the adjoining substring to be the remaining 26 tokens.  That other substring would have to be produced by NT15 via NT15 → NT9 NT9 (its first token is t120, which is not an NT5 token).  
 • However NT9 can never generate the terminal t67 (its lexical set is { t19, t60, t71, t82, t97, t110, t123 }).  Because the 26-token substring contains t67, it cannot be generated by any NT9, and hence cannot be generated by NT15 → NT9 NT9.  
 • Trying any other split puts a token such as t100, t7 or t10 at the start of one NT15 substring; but none of those tokens can be the first symbol of a string produced by NT15 (for exactly the same NT5/NT9 reasons just given).

Since neither of the only two possibilities for S can cover the string, the grammar does not generate it.

No

The only way the start symbol S can begin with the terminal t112 that heads the string is through the production

 S → NT13  NT5  
 NT13 → NT1  NT10 with NT1 → 't112'.

This forces the derivation to have

 NT5 ⇒ one single terminal (because NT5 has only lexical rules)  
 NT13 ⇒ the first 38 symbols of the string.

Since the last symbol of the whole string is t65 and NT5 has a lexical rule NT5 → 't65', the required split is

 NT13 ⇒ t112 … t35 (the first 38 tokens)  
 NT5  ⇒ t65    (the 39-th token).

So NT10 must generate the 37-symbol sequence

 t55 t117 t55 t98 t90 t3 t124 t82 t29 t31 t79 t65
 t60 t54 t95 t58 t93 t126 t104 t11 t91 t45 t67 t87
 t40 t61 t10 t27 t126 t65 t78 t55 t119 t109 t123
 t75 t35

The only rule of NT10 that can start with the terminal t55 is

 NT10 → NT2  NT16 with NT2 ⇒ first part, NT16 ⇒ remainder.

NT16 can start only

 • with a terminal in {t37, t3, t60, t57, t30, t14, t48, t73, t72, t28, t26, t15, t108, t116, t131} (its own lexical rules),  
 • or with a terminal produced by NT7 (t39, t105, t120, t133, t115),  
 • or with a terminal produced by NT2.

Scanning the sequence after the initial t55, the first symbol that could start an NT16-derivation is

 t3 (the 6-th symbol in the NT10 part).

Hence NT2 would have to produce exactly

 t55 t117 t55 t98 t90.

But NT2 cannot generate that 5-symbol string:

• its only lexical possibilities are single-token strings,  
• the binary rules NT2 → NT1 NT2, NT2 → NT2 NT7, NT2 → NT14 NT7, NT2 → NT12 NT10, NT2 → NT0 NT11 can never yield the prefix “t55 t117 …” because
 – NT1 never produces t55,  
 – NT14 produces t117 but then the next symbol must come from NT7 (t39, t105, t120, t133, t115), not t55,  
 – NT2 itself cannot yield t117 as its second symbol (its lexical set contains no t117).

Therefore NT2 cannot produce the required prefix, so NT10 cannot generate the needed 37-symbol sequence. Consequently NT13 cannot derive the first 38 tokens, and the whole string cannot be generated from S.

Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol S can expand only in one of two ways:

1. S → NT13 NT5  
2. S → NT15 NT15  

Therefore the first token of any sentence generated by the grammar must come from either NT13 (in the first case) or NT15 (in the second case).

•  NT13 can begin with only  
  – one of its own terminal productions: t113, t65, t58, t12, t20, t40, t36, t70, t10, t79, or  
  – the first token produced by NT1, NT11, NT16 or NT2 through its binary rules.  
  None of those non-terminals can ultimately yield t95 as their first token (all of their possible first-token terminals are listed in the grammar and t95 is not among them).  
  Hence NT13 can never produce a string whose first token is t95.

•  NT15 may begin with  
  – one of its own terminals (t49, t55, t67, t73, t10, t121, t24, t39, t83, t90, t71, t51, t127), or  
  – the first token generated by NT5 (if the rule NT15 → NT5 NT13 is chosen), or  
  – the first token generated by NT9 (if the rule NT15 → NT9 NT9 is chosen).  
  
  NT5’s terminals are t11, t77, t34, t31, t45, t130, t60, t38, t65 – not t95.  
  NT9 can start only with one of its own terminals (t19, t71, t82, t123, t97, t60, t110) or with the first token of NT14 (in the expansion NT9 → NT14 NT7); neither NT9’s own terminals nor NT14’s possible first tokens include t95.

Thus, regardless of which of the two start-rules is chosen, the very first token that the grammar can produce is never t95.  Since the string to be tested does begin with t95, the string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The start symbol S can expand in only two ways:  
1. S → NT13 NT7  
2. S → NT15 NT15  

Since the last token of the string is t125 – which NT7 cannot produce (NT7 only generates t39, t105, t115, t120, t133) – derivation (1) is impossible, so S must use rule (2).

For S → NT15 NT15 we need each NT15 to generate some portion of the 49-token string.

NT15 has three kinds of productions  
• terminal productions (e.g. NT15 → 't71', 't73', 't83', 't10', 't121', …)  
• NT15 → NT5 NT13  
• NT15 → NT9 NT9  

All three allow strings of arbitrary length:

– NT5 is a single terminal (t34, t36, t45, t77, t124, …) followed by the string produced by NT13.  
– NT13, via rules such as NT13 → NT1 NT10, NT13 → NT11 NT7, NT13 → NT16 NT5 and the many recursive rules inside NT1, NT10, NT11, NT16, can generate strings of any length and containing any terminals that occur in our sentence (NT10 alone can introduce NT0, and NT0 has the terminal t125, so the final token can be produced).  
– NT9 either terminates immediately (e.g. NT9 → 't19', 't71', 't110', …) or lengthens itself recursively through NT9 → NT9 NT10 and NT9 → NT7 NT0, again giving access to all needed terminals (t125 appears through the NT7 NT0 path because NT0 → 't125'). Since NT9 can be repeated (NT15 → NT9 NT9), NT15 can thus generate strings of any even length ≥2, and – through the NT5 NT13 alternative – strings of any odd length ≥1 as well.

Hence NT15 can match an arbitrary finite sequence of terminals drawn from the grammar’s vocabulary, and there is no parity or positional restriction that prevents splitting a 49-token string into two substrings, each produced by an NT15. One convenient split is:

First NT15 generates tokens 1-24  
Second NT15 generates tokens 25-49

Both substrings begin with terminals that NT15 can produce directly (t71 and t10) and, by the recursive mechanisms sketched above, each substring can be derived completely inside a single NT15.

Therefore the whole 49-token sentence can be derived from S:

S ⇒ NT15 NT15 ⇒* (tokens 1-24) (tokens 25-49)

Because such a derivation exists, the given string is in the language of the grammar.

Yes
